{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/blog/setting-the-artboard-background-color-in-adobe-illustrator/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Jack Harner","description":"Jack Harner is a Freelance Web Developer & E-Commerce Consultant based in Denver, Colorado. Shopify, BigCommerce, WordPress Dev & More.","author":"@jackharner","siteUrl":"https://jackharner.com"}},"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>Sometimes when you're working with <a href=\"/blog/tags/graphic-design\">graphic design</a> you end up working on a piece that's meant to be displayed on a non-white background, like a logo or web icon. Unfortunately, there isn't really a way to set the background color of an artboard in Adobe Illustrator, but let's look at a few workarounds that achieve the same effect.</p>\n<h2>The simplest way</h2>\n<p>The simplest, but probably not the best way of accomplishing a colored background is to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Draw out a rectangle the size of your artboard</li>\n<li>Send it to the back of the layer <code class=\"language-text\">Ctrl + Shift + [</code></li>\n<li>Lock it <code class=\"language-text\">Ctrl + 2</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>I've run into problems with this method however, where I'll go to export the file as an SVG but forget to delete the background and end up with an extra element in the code or a solid color where you wanted transparency in a PNG.</p>\n<p>Useful if you just need to check a quick background color, just don't forget to delete it when you're saving!</p>\n<p>{{{vert}}}</p>\n<h2>The better way</h2>\n<p>The better, not quite as simple way to get a colored artboard is to take advantage of the Transparency Grid. It's used to show which parts of a project are transparent and how much. To get it setup go to <code class=\"language-text\">File > Document Setup</code></p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 484px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 106.33333333333333%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Document Setup Menu\"\n        title=\"Illustrator&#39;s Document Setup Menu\"\n        src=\"/static/ea40f8ad792e177ac7347ccbff5fdef9/ff42b/document-setup.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/ea40f8ad792e177ac7347ccbff5fdef9/5a46d/document-setup.png 300w,\n/static/ea40f8ad792e177ac7347ccbff5fdef9/ff42b/document-setup.png 484w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 484px) 100vw, 484px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Illustrator&#39;s Document Setup Menu</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Under the Transparency section you need to double click on both of two color squares and set them to whatever color you want your background to be.</p>\n<p>Click OK on the Document Settings panel and then go to <code class=\"language-text\">View > Show Transparency Grid</code> You can also use the keyboard shortcut: <code class=\"language-text\">Ctrl + Shift + D</code> to toggle the Transparency Grid on and off.</p>\n<h2>There you have it, folks.</h2>\n<p>An \"Any Color You Can Think Of\" background on your artboards in Illustrator without having extra objects cluttering up your files. One thing to keep in mind though, is the document properties are set on a per-project basis, so you'll have to set it every time.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Photo by <a href=\"https://unsplash.com/@rumpf?utm_source=unsplash&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=creditCopyText\">Christina Rumpf</a> on <a href=\"https://unsplash.com/photos/XWDMmk-yW7Q?utm_source=unsplash&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=creditCopyText\">Unsplash</a></p>\n</blockquote>","excerpt":"Sometimes when you're working with graphic design you end up working on a piece that's meant to be displayed on a non-white background, like a logo or…","wordCount":{"words":317},"frontmatter":{"date":"January 13, 2023","updated":null,"title":"Setting The Artboard Background Color In Adobe Illustrator CC","subtitle":"","tags":["Graphic Design","Illustrator"],"featuredImage":{"absolutePath":"/home/runner/work/jackharner-gatsby/jackharner-gatsby/content/blog/setting-the-artboard-background-color-in-adobe-illustrator/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.jpg","childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fullWidth","backgroundColor":"#e8e8e8","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/e354bc8c3c8c724a35e1b30417afffaf/5267c/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.jpg","srcSet":"/static/e354bc8c3c8c724a35e1b30417afffaf/7284f/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.jpg 750w,\n/static/e354bc8c3c8c724a35e1b30417afffaf/29ba9/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.jpg 1080w,\n/static/e354bc8c3c8c724a35e1b30417afffaf/c8896/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.jpg 1366w,\n/static/e354bc8c3c8c724a35e1b30417afffaf/5267c/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.jpg 1920w","sizes":"100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/e354bc8c3c8c724a35e1b30417afffaf/57584/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.webp 750w,\n/static/e354bc8c3c8c724a35e1b30417afffaf/984df/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.webp 1080w,\n/static/e354bc8c3c8c724a35e1b30417afffaf/4a276/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.webp 1366w,\n/static/e354bc8c3c8c724a35e1b30417afffaf/9c00f/christina-rumpf-XWDMmk-yW7Q-unsplash.webp 1920w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"100vw"}]},"width":1,"height":0.6666666666666666}}},"ogImage":null},"fields":{"externalLink":"","externalLinkLabel":"Check It Out »","slug":"/blog/setting-the-artboard-background-color-in-adobe-illustrator/","ogImage":"","date":"January 13, 2023","unlist